"So far, I am just brainstorming, but it seems the most elegant way is to add further submodules under the `particle` directory. It currently has `pdgid`, then there could be `pythiaid` with a `PYTHIAID` class, `corsikaid` with a `CORSIKAID` class and so on and so forth.\n\nBtw, here is the doc of `particletools`, which explains its capabilities.\r\nhttps://particledatatool.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html\n\nbtw, I am happy to contribute EPOSID in a PR if we agree that adding these enums is the way to go.\n\n@HDembinski, I like your ideas, as said before. We should get in touch with Anatoli asap \u2026\r\n\r\nI do have some urgent matters to sort out and won't be able to jump immediately with developments on this front, but would be super happy if you can start on your suggestions.\r\n\r\nIn general I do think we can make a stronger package profiting from particletools, as you say.\r\n\r\nThanks a lot!\n\nBTW, @HDembinski, could you kindly get in touch with Anatoli, for collaboration? You can point him to here and also the Scikit-HEP forum. Thanks.\n\nSure, I did that with an issue on his ParticleTools repo, but I will also get in touch by email.\n\nAdding @henryiii explicitly in the loop, now that we want to move forward with a collaboration and design proposals for the inclusion of ID conversions and alike.\n\nI like the idea of (simple) classes similar to `PDGID`. A skeleton class for, say, PythiaID, can be easily sketched. I would suggest that all `XXXID` classes implement a method `to_pdgid()`, as that seems like an obvious query.\r\n\r\nWe can go and create the `particle.pythiaid`, `particle.evtgenid`, etc., submodules. Two immediate things, though:\r\n\r\n1) Are there cases where we need also a way to match names, not just IDs? How to provide these? Probably separately from the translation of IDs. So maybe we should rather have `particle.pythia`, `particle.evtgen`, `particle.pdg`, etc.?\r\nThis would imply the move `particle.pdgid.pdgid.py` to `particle.pdg.pdgid.py` - not a problem since we do anyway from `Particle import PDGID`.\r\n\r\n2) What's the ideal format to store all conversions? I would not go the way of csv/... tables but would rather store the pairs of values/names in a tuple, probably.\r\nIf I understand you, @HDembinski, we would have beasts such as `Pythia2PDGIDBiMap`, `EvtGen2PDGIDBiMap`, etc., all inheriting from the `TwoWayDict` class described in the StackOverflow link you provide above?\r\nThen one would do `Pythia2PDGIDBiMap[PDGID(211)]` or `Pythia2PDGIDBiMap[PythiaID(211)]` with no trouble...\r\nFor speed the BiMap's should be created upon import, so\r\n```\r\nfrom particle.converters import Pythia2PDGIDBiMap  # fills all translation pairs\r\n\r\nclass PythiaID(int):\r\n...\r\ndef to_pdgid(self):\r\n    return Pythia2PDGIDBiMap[self]\r\n...\r\n```\r\nThis being said, I would imagine that most users would not be playing with the BiMap's themselves, rather doing manipulations such as\r\n`Particle.from_pdgid(pythiaid.to_pdgid())`\r\nwhere, e.g.\r\n`pythiaid= PythiaID(211)`.\r\n\r\nOK, enough for a quick-start of design choices ;-). I basically brain-dumped here. Comments and suggestions more than welcome ... Thanks a lot!\n\nFor ref, the relevant programs we thought about so far are: CORSIKA, EPOS, EvtGen, Geant, Pythia, Sybill, UrQMD. Anything else?\n\nHi @afedynitch, let me know your thoughts on the above when you find time. Thanks.\n\nKind ping, @afedynitch.\n\nHi, I'm still busy, now for a different event, but we start compiling the next steps in order to estimate if and how much work that would be.\r\n\r\n#### The particletools package has the following features that might be of interest to merge into this project:\r\n\r\n1. Access to PDG data via the XML file from PYTHIA8:\r\n\r\n    These are mass, charge, lifetime, name, pdg_id and branching ratio+decay channel. Other info is available but unused, like the spin.\r\n\r\n    - ``scikit-hep/particle`` seem to directly access the PDG database, what is probably the better approach.\r\n    - ``particletools`` caches the result from parsing the XML in a pickled dictionary that accelerates the initialization time. This is one of the very important features of the package, since the applications may require initializing it frequently  \r\n\r\n2. Particle code conversions\r\n\r\n    There are a number of models that are supported for index conversion:\r\n\r\n    - QGSJet 01, II-03/-04\r\n    - UrQMD \r\n    - SIBYLL 2.X\r\n\r\n   The other \"cosmic ray\" event generators use internally proprietary code systems but also include conversions from/to PDG codes or the HEPEVT common block. I know how to access the converters, but it's not so straight forward to imagine an application, where one would handle code conversion in PYTHON instead of the FORTRAN routines.\r\n\r\n3. There is a larger package in preparation called ``impy``, also together with Hans. It is a standardized Python interface to six min-bias and AA event generators + some specialized ones. It relies on f2py and standard fortran compilers. It's used in many projects over the past years and became mature enough to publish. It seems to be quite in line with the goals of this project. You might want to take a look on gitlab.com (username)?\n\n> The particletools package has the following features that might be of interest to merge into this project:\r\n> \r\n> \r\n> Access to PDG data via the XML file from PYTHIA8:\r\n> These are mass, charge, lifetime, name, pdg_id and branching ratio+decay channel. Other info is available but unused, like the spin.\r\n> \r\n> scikit-hep/particle seem to directly access the PDG database, what is probably the better approach.\r\n> particletools caches the result from parsing the XML in a pickled dictionary that accelerates the initialization time. This is one of the very important features of the package, since the applications may require initializing it frequently\r\n\r\nI also think that the approach of accessing directly the PDG file is better. This being said, and to be comprehensive, we do use a digested CSV file that contains extended information, see examples in the README, such as\r\n```\r\n$ python -m particle search 311\r\nName: K0             ID: 311          Latex: $K^{0}$\r\nMass  = 497.611 \u00b1 0.013 MeV\r\nWidth = -1.0 MeV\r\nQ (charge)        = 0       J (total angular) = 0.0      P (space parity) = -\r\nC (charge parity) = ?       I (isospin)       = 1/2      G (G-parity)     = ?\r\n    SpinType: SpinType.PseudoScalar\r\n    Quarks: dS\r\n    Antiparticle name: K~0 (antiparticle status: Barred)\r\n```\r\nWe also do caching: the table (CSV file) is loaded the first time. I don't think you will have timing issues.\n\n> Particle code conversions\r\n> There are a number of models that are supported for index conversion:\r\n> \r\n> QGSJet 01, II-03/-04\r\n> UrQMD\r\n> SIBYLL 2.X\r\n> \r\n> The other \"cosmic ray\" event generators use internally proprietary code systems but also include conversions from/to PDG codes or the HEPEVT common block. I know how to access the converters, but it's not so straight forward to imagine an application, where one would handle code conversion in PYTHON instead of the FORTRAN routines.\r\n\r\nOn conversions: did you check the proposal I outlined above? It's very lightweight. From looking at your package we do have all PID tables. Remains to be decided how to store them here and manipulate them, hence my proposal.\n\n> There is a larger package in preparation called impy, also together with Hans. It is a standardized Python interface to six min-bias and AA event generators + some specialized ones. It relies on f2py and standard fortran compilers. It's used in many projects over the past years and became mature enough to publish. It seems to be quite in line with the goals of this project. You might want to take a look on gitlab.com (username)?\r\n\r\nThis is probably private as I did not find it at gitlab.com, even when signed in ;-).\n\n@HDembinski, you were the first one to propose a bimap. If you could have a look at the proposal above \u2026 Thanks.\n\nFYI @henryiii."